# Copy Tone — Lowercase Titles/Subtitles & Gen-Z Messaging

User-facing text follows a casual, gen-z coded tone. Lowercase applies only to title and subtitle copy.

## Rules

- **Lowercase for titles and subtitles only** — screen titles, section titles, and subtitles must be lowercase. No title case, no sentence case for these.
- **Other copy** — buttons, CTAs, labels, and body copy are not required to be lowercase; use whatever casing fits the context.
- **Casual and friendly** — write like you're texting a friend, not drafting a corporate email.
- **Proper nouns keep casing** — brand names (Szpont, Google, Apple, Android) and abbreviations (DD, MM) retain their original casing.
- **No exclamation inflation** — one exclamation mark max per screen; prefer periods or no punctuation on short labels.

## Common translation block

Shared, repeated labels (continue, back, etc.) live in the top-level `"common"` block in the locale JSON files so they aren't duplicated across feature blocks.

```json
"common": {
  "continue": "continue",
  "back": "back"
}
```

Reference them as `t('common.continue')`, `t('common.back')`, etc.

Before adding a new label to a feature block, check whether `common` already has it.

## Examples (titles & subtitles)

```
"welcome"           ✅
"Welcome"           ❌
"let's go"          ✅
"Let's Go"          ❌
"get started"       ✅
"Get Started"       ❌
"open settings"     ✅
"Open Settings"     ❌
"sign in with Google" ✅  (title/subtitle)
```
